14 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
15 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
16 Article – Family Law
17 5–701.
18 (a) Except as otherwise provided in § 5–705.1 of this subtitle, in this subtitle the
19 following words have the meanings indicated.
20 (b) (1) “Abuse” means:
21 (i) the physical or mental injury of a child under circumstances that
22 indicate that the child’s health or welfare is harmed or at substantial risk of being harmed
23 by:
24 1. a parent;
25 2. a household member or family member;
26 3. a person who has permanent or temporary care or custody
27 of the child;
28 4. a person who has responsibility for supervision of the
29 child; or
30 5. a person who, because of the person’s position or
31 occupation, exercises authority over the child;
32 (ii) sexual abuse of a child, whether physical injuries are sustained
33 or not; or

SENATE BILL 907 3
1 (iii) labor trafficking of a child by any individual.
2 (2) “ABUSE” INCLUDES FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION, AS DEFINED
3 IN § 20–601 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
4 (3) “Abuse” does not include the physical injury of a child by accidental
5 means.
6 5–704.
7 (a) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, including any law on privileged
8 communications, each health practitioner, police officer, educator, or human service
9 worker, acting in a professional capacity in this State who has reason to believe that a child
10 has been subjected to abuse or neglect:
11 (1) shall notify the local department or the appropriate law enforcement
12 agency; and
13 (2) if acting as a staff member of a hospital, public health agency, child care
14 institution, juvenile detention center, school, or similar institution, shall immediately
15 notify and give all information required by this section to the head of the institution or the
16 designee of the head.
17 (b) (1) An individual who notifies the appropriate authorities under subsection
18 (a) of this section shall make:
19 (i) an oral report, by telephone or direct communication, as soon as
20 possible to the local department or appropriate law enforcement agency; and
21 (ii) a written report:
22 1. to the local department not later than 48 hours after the
23 contact, examination, attention, or treatment that caused the individual to believe that the
24 child had been subjected to abuse or neglect; and
25 2. with a copy to the local State’s Attorney.
26 (2) (i) An agency to which an oral report of suspected abuse or neglect
27 is made under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall immediately notify the other agency.
28 (ii) This paragraph does not prohibit a local department and an
29 appropriate law enforcement agency from agreeing to cooperative arrangements.
30 (c) Insofar as is reasonably possible, an individual who makes a report under this
31 section shall include in the report the following information:

4 SENATE BILL 907
1 (1) the name, age, and home address of the child;
2 (2) the name and home address of the child’s parent or other person who is
3 responsible for the child’s care;
4 (3) the whereabouts of the child;
5 (4) the nature and extent of the abuse or neglect of the child, including any
6 evidence or information available to the reporter concerning possible previous instances of
7 abuse or neglect; and
8 (5) any other information that would help to determine:
9 (i) the cause of the suspected abuse or neglect; and
10 (ii) the identity of any individual responsible for the abuse or neglect.
11 Article – Health – General
12 20–601.
13 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION” MEANS A PROCEDURE
14 PERFORMED FOR NONMEDICAL REASONS THAT INVOLVES PARTIAL OR TOTAL
15 REMOVAL OF OR OTHER INJURY TO THE EXTERNAL FEMALE GENITALIA, INCLUDING:
16 (1) A CLITORIDECTOMY OR THE PARTIAL OR TOTAL REMOVAL OF THE
17 CLITORIS, PREPUCE, OR CLITORAL HOOD;
18 (2) EXCISION OR THE PARTIAL OR TOTAL REMOVAL, WITH OR
19 WITHOUT EXCISION OF THE CLITORIS, OF THE LABIA MINORA, WITH OR WITHOUT
20 REMOVAL OF THE LABIA MAJORA;
21 (3) INFIBULATION OR THE NARROWING OF THE VAGINAL OPENING,
22 WITH OR WITHOUT EXCISION OF THE CLITORIS; OR
23 (4) ANY OTHER PROCEDURE THAT IS HARMFUL TO THE EXTERNAL
24 FEMALE GENITALIA, INCLUDING PRICKING, PIERCING, INCISING, SCRAPING, OR
25 CAUTERIZING THE GENITAL AREA.
26 [20–601.] 20–602.
27 (a) Except as provided in [§ 20–602] § 20–603 of this subtitle, a person [who
28 circumcises, excises, or infibulates the whole or any part of the labia majora or labia minora
29 or clitoris of an individual who is under the age of 18 years is guilty of] MAY NOT:

SENATE BILL 907 5
1 (1) KNOWINGLY PERFORM, ATTEMPT TO PERFORM, OR CONSPIRE TO
2 PERFORM female genital mutilation ON AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS UNDER THE AGE OF 18
3 YEARS; OR
4 (2) TRANSPORT AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS UNDER THE AGE OF 18 YEARS
5 OUT OF THE STATE FOR THE PURPOSE OF PERFORMING OR FACILITATING THE
6 PERFORMANCE OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION ON THE INDIVIDUAL.
7 (b) Except as provided in [§ 20–602] § 20–603 of this subtitle, a parent, guardian,
8 or other individual is guilty of female genital mutilation if the individual:
9 (1) Is legally responsible and charged with the care or custody of a child
10 under the age of 18 years; and
11 (2) Knowingly consents to [the circumcision, excision, or infibulation of the
12 whole or any part of the labia majora or labia minora or clitoris of] THE PERFORMANCE
13 OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION ON the child.
14 [20–602.] 20–603.
15 (a) A surgical operation is not a violation of this subtitle if the operation is
16 necessary to the health of the individual on whom it is performed and is performed by a
17 person licensed in the State as a medical practitioner.
18 (b) In determining whether an operation is necessary to the health of the
19 individual, no account may be taken of the belief on the part of any individual that the
20 operation is required as a matter of custom or ritual.
21 [20–603.] 20–604.
22 (A) A person who violates the provisions of this subtitle is guilty of a felony and
23 on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding [5] 10 years or a fine not exceeding
24 [$5,000] $10,000 or both.
25 (B) IF AN INDIVIDUAL WHO HOLDS A LICENSE ISSUED UNDER THE HEALTH
26 OCCUPATIONS ARTICLE IS CONVICTED OF, ENTERS A PLEA OF GUILTY OR OF NOLO
27 CONTENDERE FOR, OR RECEIVES PROBATION BEFORE JUDGMENT FOR A VIOLATION
28 OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE APPLICABLE HEALTH OCCUPATIONS BOARD SHALL REVOKE
29 THE LICENSE OF THE INDIVIDUAL.
30 20–605.
31 (A) A VICTIM OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION PERFORMED IN VIOLATION
32 OF THIS SUBTITLE MAY FILE AN ACTION IN THE CIRCUIT COURT IN THE COUNTY IN
33 WHICH THE VIOLATION OCCURRED OR THE VICTIM RESIDES.

6 SENATE BILL 907
1 (B) IF THE COURT FINDS THAT A PERSON VIOLATED THIS SUBTITLE, THE
2 COURT MAY AWARD THE PLAINTIFF:
3 (1) ACTUAL DAMAGES;
4 (2) COMPENSATORY DAMAGES;
5 (3) PUNITIVE DAMAGES;
6 (4) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES, COURT COSTS, AND LITIGATION
7 EXPENSES, INCLUDING EXPERT WITNESS FEES AND EXPENSES; AND
8 (5) ANY OTHER APPROPRIATE RELIEF.
9 (C) AN ACTION BROUGHT UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION SHALL
10 BE FILED THE LATER OF:
11 (1) NOT MORE THAN 10 YEARS AFTER THE DATE ON WHICH THE
12 VIOLATION OCCURRED; OR
13 (2) THE DATE ON WHICH THE VICTIM OF THE VIOLATION REACHES 28
14 YEARS OF AGE.
15 20–606.
16 (A) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2027, THE
17 DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE SOCIAL SERVICES ADMINISTRATION,
18 STATE AND LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES, AND OTHER APPROPRIATE
19 GOVERNMENT AGENCIES AND PUBLIC AND PRIVATE ORGANIZATIONS, SHALL
20 SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF
21 THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, CONTAINING DE–IDENTIFIED AND
22 DISAGGREGATED DATA ON THE NUMBER OF:
23 (1) REPORTS OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION SUBMITTED IN
24 ACCORDANCE WITH § 5–704 OF THE FAMILY LAW ARTICLE;
25 (2) INDIVIDUALS PROSECUTED FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS SUBTITLE;
26 (3) INDIVIDUALS CONVICTED OF A VIOLATION OF THIS SUBTITLE;
27 (4) CIVIL ACTIONS FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SUBTITLE; AND

SENATE BILL 907 7
1 (5) CIVIL ACTIONS UNDER THIS SUBTITLE IN WHICH A JUDGMENT
2 WAS ENTERED, WHETHER BY SETTLEMENT OR ADJUDICATION.
3 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL MAKE THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER
4 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION AVAILABLE TO THE PUBLIC.
5 20–607.
6 THE DEPARTMENT, IN COLLABORATION WITH COMMUNITY–BASED
7 ORGANIZATIONS, SHALL:
8 (1) DEVELOP AND PUBLISH CULTURALLY AND LINGUISTICALLY
9 APPROPRIATE EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS ON FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION,
10 INCLUDING:
11 (I) THE SIGNS THAT AN INDIVIDUAL HAS BEEN SUBJECTED TO
12 FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION;
13 (II) THE PHYSICAL AND MENTAL HEALTH RISKS CAUSED BY
14 FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION; AND
15 (III) THE CRIMINAL PENALTIES FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS
16 SUBTITLE; AND
17 (2) DISTRIBUTE THE EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS DESCRIBED UNDER
18 ITEM (1) OF THIS SECTION TO:
19 (I) HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS;
20 (II) LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES;
21 (III) SCHOOLS;
22 (IV) THE PUBLIC; AND
23 (V) ANY OTHER PROFESSIONAL OR COMMUNITY–BASED
24 ORGANIZATIONS THAT MAY WORK OR INTERACT WITH INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE AT
25 RISK OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION.
26 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
27 October 1, 2026.

